Literate programming
====================

Lets write and test a useful library:

.. code-block:: c

    // This is a C library
    @functionDeclarations




.. code-block:: c

    // This is a C library
    @functionImplementations




The ``fib`` function computes Fibonacci's numbers:

.. code-block:: C

    int fib(int n);




.. code-block:: C

    int fib(int n)
    {
        return (n < 2) ? 1 : fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
    }




The ``fact`` function computes factorial numbers:

.. code-block:: C

    int fact(int n);



.. code-block:: C

    int fact(int n)
    {
        return (n <= 1) ? 1 : n * fact(n-1);
    }




Some tests of ``mylib.c``:

.. code-block:: C

    #include <stdio.h>
    #include <stdlib.h>
    
    #include "mylib.h"
    
    int main(int argc, char * argv[])
    {
        int i;
        for (i = 1; i < argc; i++)
        {
            int n = atoi(argv[i]);
            printf("fact(%d) = %3d; fib(%d) = %3d\n", n, fact(n), n, fib(n));
        }
        return 0;
    }









``mylibtest 0 1 2 3 4 5`` outputs::

    fact(0) =   1; fib(0) =   1
    fact(1) =   1; fib(1) =   1
    fact(2) =   2; fib(2) =   2
    fact(3) =   6; fib(3) =   3
    fact(4) =  24; fib(4) =   5
    fact(5) = 120; fib(5) =   8


